  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The data set of "Tmdb-movies" contains statistics about films from 1960 to 2015, their ratings, and some information such as production year, revenue, budget, actors, etc. We'll show the data and discovering quality and tightness issues then we clean that data and answer the mentioned questions.

  • which genre have the highest revenue ?
  • which lead actor have the highest revenue ?
  • Does rating affects revenue ?
  • What year was the largest number of films produced?
  • What is the highest-grossing movie annually?
  • which director have the highest revenues ?
  • Does runtime affects revenues ?
  • Does increasing the budget corresponds to increased rating and revenue or not ?
  • What are the statistics on movie revenues in the year 2010?
  • What year did the budget reach its peak, and in which year was the highest revenue obtained?

Assess Data¶

QUALTIY DIMENSIONS¶

  • completeness
    • missing values in (cast, director , imdb_id, genres)
  • validity
    • id is a integer not a string
    • release_year is a integer not a string
  • Data types(consistency issues):
    • ( runtime ) convert values ( 0 ) to ( mean of runtime )
  • accurancy
    • ( df_movie ) Erroneous datatype ( release_date )

Tidiness¶

  • Drop column ( homepage,tagline, keywords, production_companies )
  • Drop duplicate row
  • Drop row that revenue = 0 and budget = 0

Fixing columns that contain of nan values¶

 (cast, director ,imdb_id , genres , revenue)

 Fill 0 value in column( runtime ) by mean of values column

Code

In [18]:
df_movie_clean['cast'].fillna('No cast',inplace = True)
df_movie_clean['director'].fillna('No director',inplace = True)
df_movie_clean['imdb_id'].fillna('No imdb_id',inplace = True)
df_movie_clean['overview'].fillna('No overview',inplace = True)
df_movie_clean['genres'].fillna('No genres',inplace = True)
df_movie_clean['runtime'] = df_movie_clean['runtime'].replace(0, df_movie_clean['runtime'].mean())

we will create a list of the genre to find the total revenue for each genre

In [22]:
list_genre =df_movie_clean['genres']  #list of genre
dict_revenue_genre = {}
for genre in list_genre:
    revenue_genre = df_movie_clean[df_movie_clean['genres'] == genre]['revenue'].sum()
    dict_revenue_genre[genre]=revenue_genre
In [23]:
# to extract genre by using high revenue
high_revenue = max(dict_revenue_genre.values())
genre = ''
for genres , revenue in dict_revenue_genre.items():
    if high_revenue== revenue:
        genre = genres
        break
        
genre , high_revenue

Question 2 : What is the highest-grossing movie annually?¶

We will create a list of unique years to find the max of revenue for each year

In [27]:
list_years = df_movie_clean['release_year'].unique() # list of unique years
dict_yr_mov = {}
for year in list_years:
        high_revenue = max(df_movie_clean[df_movie_clean['release_year'] == year]['revenue'])
        title = df_movie_clean[(df_movie_clean['release_year'] == year) & (df_movie_clean['revenue'] == high_revenue)]['original_title'].to_string(index=False)
        dict_yr_mov[year] = title
In [28]:
print("Answer :We can notice that the highest film in the year 2015 was:"+ dict_yr_mov['2015']+" and 2014 was:"+dict_yr_mov['2014']+" and 2013 was:"+dict_yr_mov['2013']
+"and we can know the rest of the films that have received the highest revenues since the year 1960.")

Answer :We can notice that the highest film in the year 2015 was: Star Wars: The Force Awakens and 2014 was: The Hobbit: The Battle of the Five Armies and 2013 was: Frozenand we can know the rest of the films that have received the highest revenues since the year 1960.

Answer :It is evident from the chart that we cannot have an explicit relationship between revenues and the average rating, as we notice that the revenue after 5 average_rating is increasing, then after passing 7 average_rating, it begins to decline, and this indicates that there is no relationship between them.
